values.comments:
This is an intermediate course in biology providing an overview of the physiology of vertebrates, especially concerning the human organ systems. The prerequisite for the class is BIOL102, BIOL121, or BIOL124. The course consists of a co-taught lecture and a TA-run recitation, and grading is based on four equal-weight, non-cumulative exams and some homework problems. One of two texts is recommended: Boron's Human Physiology or Guyton's Textbook of Medical Physiology, which students rated as “excellent resources.”&#8232;

Most students felt that this course was “interesting” and “beneficial,” if somewhat disorganized. However, some noted that much of the material had already been covered in first-year biology, and that as a result they learned relatively little. Overall, students found the course good for specific details about particular systems, though some would have preferred more discussion of animal physiology. Other students felt that the content was “too quantitative,” involving more math and physics than expected, while lacking in depth of anatomical concepts.&#8232;

In general, students liked Professor Rome, noting in particular his humor, enthusiasm for teaching, and intelligence. Prof. Rome's teaching style was “adequate at explaining the course concepts,” though some students felt his lectures should have had more clarity and more closely followed the textbook. However, students found him “open to questions” and easily accessible for help outside of lecture.

Most students in this course were Biology majors and/or pre-meds, which students felt generated a highly competitive atmosphere. Lecture slides were not made available, making it difficult to get makeup notes. Students had wildly different views about the four non-cumulative exams, ranging from “insultingly easy” to “could have been more challenging” to “purposefully difficult to generate a curve.” The general consensus was that exams were “fair,” but the lack of a relational curve was not. Most felt that the workload required for the class was “not too high” save for studying.
